        <div class="tab-content" id="tab-usage" style="display:none;padding-top:32px;">
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="when-to-use" class="doc-section-title">When and Where to Use</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Progress bars communicate measurable completion status across uploads, processing, and system operations.</p>
            <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px;margin-top:24px;">
              <div style="padding:24px;background:var(--prism-surface);border:1px solid var(--prism-border);border-radius:12px;">
                <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--prism-text);margin-bottom:16px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;"><svg width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="#2563eb" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>When to use</h3>
                <ul class="doc-list" style="border:none;background:transparent;padding-left:20px;font-size:14.5px;">
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">To show <strong>measurable progress</strong> toward a known completion point (file upload, form completion, steps completed).</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">To communicate <strong>system status</strong> during a background operation (syncing, processing, building).</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">When the user benefits from knowing <strong>how much remains</strong>, not just that something is happening.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;">Use <strong>Indeterminate</strong> when the duration or percentage cannot be calculated.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;">Use <strong>Success / Warning / Error</strong> variants when the completion state carries a semantic outcome.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div style="padding:24px;background:var(--prism-surface);border:1px solid var(--prism-border);border-radius:12px;">
                <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;color:var(--prism-text);margin-bottom:16px;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;"><svg width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="#e42527" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>When NOT to use</h3>
                <ul class="doc-list" style="border:none;background:transparent;padding-left:20px;font-size:14.5px;">
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Step-by-step workflows</strong> &#8212; use a Wizard instead. Progress bars don't communicate discrete steps clearly.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Circular loading</strong> &#8212; use Progress Loader for spinners inside buttons or inline loaders.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Binary complete / incomplete</strong> &#8212; use a Checkbox or a simple status indicator.</li>
                  <li style="border:none;background:transparent;"><strong>Page-level loading</strong> &#8212; use a top-of-page slim bar (e.g. NProgress pattern), not a full-width labelled progress bar.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <hr class="doc-divider"/>
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="indeterminate-mode" class="doc-section-title">Indeterminate Mode</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">When the total duration or steps of an operation are unknown, use variant="Indeterminate". The fill stub is a fixed-width segment (~33% of the track) that sweeps from left to right in a continuous animation.</p>
            <ul class="doc-list">
              <li><strong>Value label:</strong> Render "&#8212;" (em dash) or omit it entirely. Do not show "0%" &#8212; that implies 0% is known, which contradicts the indeterminate state.</li>
              <li><strong>Animation:</strong> Apply <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">overflow: hidden</code> on the Track element so the fill clips at the track boundaries.</li>
              <li><strong>Reduced motion:</strong> Respect <code style="font-family:monospace;font-size:13px;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:6px;background:rgba(37,99,235,0.06);color:var(--prism-violet);">prefers-reduced-motion</code> &#8212; pause the animation and show a static 33% fill.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <hr class="doc-divider"/>
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="detailed-guidelines" class="doc-section-title">Complete Do's and Don'ts</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Guidelines for effective progress bar usage.</p>
            <div class="do-dont-grid">
              <div class="do-card"><span class="card-label">Do</span><ul>
                <li><strong>Use Large for prominent page-level progress;</strong> Small for dense lists or tables.</li>
                <li><strong>Keep the label concise</strong> (2&#8211;4 words: "Upload progress", "Storage used").</li>
                <li><strong>Show the % value</strong> alongside the bar so users can read the exact number.</li>
                <li><strong>Use Indeterminate</strong> when duration cannot be computed.</li>
                <li><strong>Transition to Success</strong> variant at 100% completion.</li>
                <li><strong>Set width: 100%</strong> in code so the bar fills its container.</li>
                <li><strong>Animate fill width</strong> with transition: width 300ms ease.</li>
                <li><strong>Respect prefers-reduced-motion</strong> &#8212; use instant updates instead of animations.</li>
              </ul></div>
              <div class="dont-card"><span class="card-label">Don't</span><ul>
                <li><strong>Use Large inside a compact list item.</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Write a full sentence</strong> as the label.</li>
                <li><strong>Rely on bar width alone</strong> for precision &#8212; perception is inaccurate.</li>
                <li><strong>Show 0% or a frozen bar</strong> while waiting &#8212; it implies the operation is stuck.</li>
                <li><strong>Leave the bar in Default</strong> state after completion.</li>
                <li><strong>Reset to 0% on error</strong> without feedback.</li>
                <li><strong>Use Warning</strong> for purely in-progress states.</li>
                <li><strong>Hard-code the 280 px</strong> canvas width.</li>
                <li><strong>Force animations</strong> regardless of user preference.</li>
              </ul></div>
            </div>
          </div>
